- large seabird
- predominantly dark plumage
- black or dark brown feathers
- long, narrow wings
- distinctive white or pale gray face
- strong, hooked beak, often dark in color
- webbed feet
- relatively long lifespan indicated by their mature and robust appearance
- often seen soaring over open oceans or resting on the water

- large seabird
- predominantly white head and body
- dark, blackish-gray wings and back
- white underbelly and tail
- long, slender wings with a wingspan of about 2 meters (6.5 feet)
- hooked, pink or yellowish beak
- dark eye patch
- webbed feet
- often seen gliding over the ocean or nesting on the ground
- distinctive nasal tubes on the beak

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Sooty Albatross in a photo:
- large seabird
- sooty brown or dark grey plumage
- slender, long wings
- white eye-ring
- dark, hooked bill with a yellow line along the lower mandible
- long, tapered tail
- webbed feet
- typically seen gliding over the ocean or nesting on steep cliffs

- medium-sized bird
- black glossy plumage
- long tail
- prominent, thick, and deeply grooved bill
- slightly arched shape of the bill
- short wings
- downward-curved, sharp claws

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Crested Auklet in a photo:
- medium-sized seabird
- black or dark gray plumage
- prominent crest of stiff, forward-curving feathers on the forehead
- bright orange bill
- white facial plumes extending back from the eyes
- small, rounded wings
- stout body
- short tail
- webbed feet

- small seabird
- relatively chunky body
- short neck
- black or dark gray (non-breeding) feathers with white underparts
- in breeding season: predominantly black with white to brownish streaks
- small, stubby, orange beak
- white face with dark eye-stripe or dark face mask
- small, rounded wings
- legs and feet set far back on the body, often appearing black or gray

- small seabird
- predominantly black or dark plumage with white underparts
- short, stout, and bright orange or red bill
- white plumes extending behind the eyes
- short wings
- webbed feet
- typically found in coastal areas or on rocky cliffs
- often seen alone or in small groups

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Rhinoceros Auklet in a photo:
- medium-sized seabird
- thick, orange bill with a distinctive horn-like extension at the base during breeding season
- dark plumage, generally dark grey or black on top
- white underparts
- small, rounded wings
- relatively short tail
- often seen with thin white plumes extending behind the eyes during breeding season
- webbed feet

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Brewer Blackbird in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- glossy black feathers (males) or dark brown feathers (females)
- pale yellow or whitish eyes
- slender body
- conical, pointed bill
- relatively long legs
- iridescent sheen on feathers (noticeable in males)
- short, square-tailed appearance

- medium-sized bird
- predominantly black plumage
- bright red shoulder patches (visible on males)
- yellow or orange border around the red shoulder patches
- slender, pointed bill
- relatively long tail
- females and juveniles may have streaky brown plumage with lighter underneath
- often seen perched on cattails, reeds, or other vegetation near water

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Rusty Blackbird in a photo:
- medium-sized songbird
- rusty or rusty-edged feathers, especially in fall and winter
- bright yellow eyes
- slender, slightly curved bill
- black or dark brown plumage during breeding season for males
- females have more subdued, brownish plumage
- long and sturdy legs
- often seen near wet, marshy areas

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Yellow-headed Blackbird in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- bright yellow head and chest
- black body and wings
- white wing patches visible in flight
- conical black beak
- dark eyes
- slender legs and feet

- small bird
- black and white plumage (adult male during breeding season)
- yellowish patch on the back of the head (adult male during breeding season)
- streaked brown and buff plumage (females and non-breeding males)
- pointed bill
- long tail with white edges
- compact body and short neck
- can often be seen perched on tall grasses or in fields

There are several useful visual features to tell there is an Indigo Bunting in a photo:
- small bird
- vibrant blue plumage (males, especially during breeding season)
- brownish or streaked plumage (females and non-breeding males)
- conical, seed-eating beak
- dark eyes
- short tail 
- often seen perched on branches or wires in open fields or edges of forests

- small songbird
- bright blue plumage on the head, back, and tail in males
- rusty-orange chest
- white belly
- conical beak
- females and juveniles have duller colors, with brownish hues
- often seen perched on branches or foraging on the ground
- short, pointed wings

- small songbird
- brightly colored plumage
- males have blue heads, red underparts, and green backs
- females and immature birds are greenish overall
- pointed beak
- medium-length tail
- predominantly found in brushy areas and woodland edges

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Cardinal in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- vibrant red plumage (male)
- brownish or dull red plumage (female)
- crest on top of the head
- black mask around the face extending to the throat
- stout, conical orange or red bill
- long tail feathers
- distinctive, pointed wings

- medium-sized bird
- distinctive greenish-brown plumage
- white spots on the throat, chest, and underparts
- robust build
- dark eyes
- relatively strong and curved beak
- short, rounded wings
- tail of moderate length
- habitat often consisting of rainforest or dense shrubbery

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Gray Catbird in a photo:
- medium-sized songbird
- predominantly slate-gray body
- darker cap on the head
- blackish tail
- chestnut-colored patch under the tail
- slender, slightly curved bill
- black legs and feet
- often seen perched upright

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Yellow-breasted Chat in a photo:
- medium-sized songbird
- bright yellow throat and breast
- olive-green back and wings
- white belly
- long tail often held upright
- stout bill
- white "spectacles" or markings around the eyes
- grayish head with a darker crown

- Small to medium-sized bird
- Black upper body and head (males) or brown upper body and head (females)
- White belly and sides with rufous or orange flanks
- Long black tail with white corners
- Thick, conical beak
- Red or red-brown eyes
- Hooked bill
- White flashes in wings
- Often seen hopping on the ground or low in shrubs

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Chuck-will's-widow in a photo:
- medium to large nocturnal bird
- cryptically colored plumage
- mottled brown, black, and gray feathers
- large, rounded head
- very short bill
- large mouth opening
- long wings
- long tail with rounded tips
- white or buffy throat patch in males
- bristly feathers around the beak

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Brandt Cormorant in a photo:
- medium to large-sized bird
- predominantly black or dark brown plumage
- striking blue facial skin (breeding season) or duller facial color (non-breeding season)
- slender, hooked bill
- long, lean neck
- webbed feet
- often seen with wings spread out to dry
- usually found near coastal waters or large bodies of water

- black or dark plumage
- bright red or orange face, particularly around the base of the bill
- long, slender neck
- relatively short tail
- webbed feet
- long, hooked bill
- white patches on sides during breeding season
- typically seen in coastal or marine environments

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Pelagic Cormorant in a photo:
- slender seabird
- glossy black plumage with a greenish or purplish sheen
- long neck
- thin, hooked bill
- small, rounded head
- a distinctive red face patch during the breeding season
- white flank patches near the thighs during the breeding season
- often seen in a streamlined, low-water posture when swimming
- typically found in coastal and marine environments

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Bronzed Cowbird in a photo:
- Stocky body
- Glossy, iridescent black plumage (bronze-green sheen)
- Red eyes
- Thick neck
- Stout, conical bill (short and thick)
- Short tail
- Adult males have a more pronounced iridescent sheen compared to females or juveniles, which may appear duller and browner

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Shiny Cowbird in a photo:
- small to medium-sized bird
- glossy, iridescent plumage
- males typically have shiny, black or dark iridescent feathers
- females are generally duller, with brownish or greyish plumage
- short, conical bill
- relatively short tail
- black eyes
- sturdy legs and feet

Sorry about the incomplete response! Here are the useful visual features to tell there is a Brown Creeper in a photo:

- small, slender bird
- brown, streaked back with white spots
- white underparts
- long, stiff tail used for support
- down-curved bill
- typically found clinging to tree trunks and branches
- camouflage pattern that blends with tree bark

There are several useful visual features to tell there is an American Crow in a photo:
- Medium to large-sized bird
- All-black plumage, including feathers and beak
- Strong, stout bill
- Fan-shaped tail
- Long, pointed wings
- Black legs and feet
- Glossy sheen to the feathers
- Often seen perching on trees, wires, or scavenging on the ground

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Fish Crow in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- entirely black plumage
- glossy or iridescent sheen on feathers
- relatively short tail
- stout, slightly curved beak
- dark eyes
- legs and feet are black
- throat feathers that appear more fluffed when calling
- often seen near water sources like coasts, rivers, or marshes

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Black-billed Cuckoo in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- slender body
- mainly brown upper parts
- white underparts
- black bill, slightly curved
- red eye ring
- long tail, often with white spots on the underside
- relatively long wings
- thin, slightly curved legs and feet

- medium-sized bird
- greyish upperparts and pale underparts
- buffy or cream-colored chest
- yellow or orange bill with a curved shape
- long, graduated tail with white spots
- bold, black mask through the eyes
- white markings on the wings
- generally seen perched in mangrove or coastal forests

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Yellow-billed Cuckoo in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- slender body
- long tail with white spots on the underside
- yellow lower mandible (the lower part of the beak)
- curved upper mandible (the upper part of the beak)
- brownish upperparts
- white underparts
- cinnamon-colored wing patches
- yellow eye-ring
- relatively long and pointed wings

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Gray-crowned-Rosy Finch in a photo:
- medium-sized finch
- gray head with a distinctively lighter gray or whitish crown
- pinkish or rosy feathers on the belly, rump, and wings
- black forehead and throat
- stout, conical bill
- brownish-gray back and wings
- dark legs and feet
- often seen in flocks, especially during winter

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Purple Finch in a photo:
- Compact, medium-sized finch
- Males have a raspberry red coloration on the head, chest, and back
- Females are streaked brown with a white eyebrow and no red coloration
- Short, conical, and stout beak
- Forked tail
- Brown streaks on white underparts (for females)
- Wings and back may have darker brown streaking
- Often seen perched on tree branches or at bird feeders

- medium-sized woodpecker
- brownish body with black barring on the back and wings
- black crescent-shaped patch on the chest
- spotted breast and belly
- red nape (back of the neck) in the Eastern form, or red malar (mustache) stripe in the Western form
- white rump visible in flight
- long, slightly curved bill
- yellow or red shafts on the flight feathers, depending on the geographical region (yellow in the East, red in the West)
- prominent, rounded head

There are several useful visual features to tell there is an Acadian Flycatcher in a photo:
- Small to medium-sized bird
- Olive-green upperparts
- Pale underparts, often with a yellowish tinge
- Short, thin bill
- White or light-colored eye ring
- Two white or light-colored wing bars
- Slightly crested head
- Often seen perched in a slightly upright posture
- Generally found in forested or wooded areas

- medium-sized bird
- prominent crest on the head
- olive-green upperparts
- grayish throat and chest
- bright yellow belly
- rust-colored (rufous) tail and wings
- large, hooked bill
- upright posture
- often found perched on branches in wooded areas

- small size (approximately 5–5.75 inches in length)
- olive-gray upperparts
- whitish underparts
- white or slightly yellowish wing bars
- distinct white eye-ring
- short, narrow bill with a black tip
- relatively short tail
- perch on branches with upright posture
- often seen in wooded or forested areas

- small to medium-sized bird
- dark olive-gray upperparts
- white or light-colored underparts with a distinctive dark vest or patch on the sides of the breast
- short, wide, and slightly hooked bill
- upright posture when perched
- generally found on high perches, such as dead branches or the tops of trees
- long wings and tail, with the tail often appearing slightly notched when spread

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Scissor-tailed Flycatcher in a photo:
- slender, elongated body
- predominantly light grey and white plumage
- distinctively long forked tail, resembling scissors
- patches of black on wings
- salmon-pink or reddish sides and underwings
- small, slightly rounded head
- thin, pointed bill
- perching on branches or flying in an open sky

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Vermilion Flycatcher in a photo:
- Small songbird
- Bright red plumage, particularly in males (head and underparts)
- Dark brown or black wings and tail
- Females are generally brownish with a faint peach wash on the belly
- Short, straight black beak
- Medium length tail, often slightly rounded
- Perched on branches, fences, or other elevated perches

- Small songbird
- Yellowish belly
- Olive-green upperparts
- White or light-colored wing bars
- Slightly rounded head with a short crest 
- Beady black eyes
- Short, broad bill 
- Slight eyering (either complete or partial)
- Indistinct streaks or mottling on flanks

- large seabird
- black or dark plumage
- sharply pointed wings which are long and slender
- deeply forked tail
- long, hooked bill
- males typically have a distinctive red gular sac (throat pouch) which they can inflate
- females and juveniles have white markings on their underparts
- often observed gliding or soaring with minimal wing flaps

- seabird
- medium-sized body
- stout, tubular beak with a prominent nasal tube on top
- grey and white plumage
- rounded head
- short, thick neck
- relatively short wings with a wingspan of about 102-112 cm (40-44 inches)
- tail is short and squared-off
- dark eyes
- often seen gliding over the ocean
- able to excrete salt through nasal passages

- Medium-sized duck
- Mottled brown or gray body
- White patch on the rear end of the wing (visible in flight)
- Black rump and tail
- Male: distinct pattern with a gray body and black bill
- Female: mottled brown with an orange and black bill
- Both sexes: slight crest on the head
- Rounded head profile
- Slender neck
- Legs and feet are generally orange or yellow

These features should help in identifying a Gadwall in a photograph.

There are several useful visual features to tell there is an American Goldfinch in a photo:
- Small, seed-eating bird
- Bright yellow plumage (in males during the breeding season)
- Black wings with white markings
- Black forehead (in males during the breeding season)
- White underbelly
- Conical, pinkish beak
- Slightly forked tail
- Olive-brown or dull yellow plumage (in non-breeding males, females, and juveniles)

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a European Goldfinch in a photo:
- small songbird
- red face
- black and white head
- yellow patch on wings
- brown back
- white underparts
- conical beak
- light brown legs and feet

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Boat-tailed Grackle in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- long, keel-shaped tail
- glossy black plumage (males) or brownish plumage (females)
- iridescent sheen (males)
- long, slender bill
- yellow or pale eyes
- relatively long legs

- small waterbird
- black neck and upper body
- distinctive golden tufts on either side of the head (during breeding season)
- red eyes
- slender, pointed bill
- black, grey, or brown feathers on the back and wings
- white underparts
- lobed toes and reduced webs for swimming
- often seen in a floating or diving posture in the water

- small waterbird
- distinctive "horns" of yellowish feathers behind the eyes, especially in breeding plumage
- red eyes
- dark head and neck
- black cap
- contrasting black and rufous (reddish-brown) body during breeding season
- lighter, more subdued gray and white coloring during non-breeding season
- short, straight bill
- often seen on water, diving for food

- small water bird
- compact body with a short neck
- brownish coloring with lighter underparts
- pale, thick bill with a distinctive dark ring ("pied" pattern) around it
- small, rounded head
- dark crown and nape
- lobed toes
- found in water habitats like ponds, lakes, and marshes
- often seen swimming low in the water

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Western Grebe in a photo:
- slender, elongated neck
- black and white plumage
- red eyes
- sharp, yellow bill
- distinctive black cap extending above the eyes
- white cheeks
- usually seen on water bodies
- elongated body
- lobed toes
- webbed feet

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Blue Grosbeak in a photo:
- medium-sized songbird
- vibrant blue plumage (males) or brownish color (females)
- thick, conical silver beak
- two rusty wing bars
- short tail
- dark legs
- typically found perched on shrubs or wires or amidst tall grasses and vegetation

- Medium-sized bird
- Thick, conical bill (often pale or yellowish)
- Yellow and black plumage in males
- Brownish-gray plumage with some yellow accents in females
- White wing patches
- Short tail
- Stocky body
- Bright yellow forehead and eye stripe (males)
- Black head cap (males)

- medium-sized finch
- rounded body
- thick, conical bill
- males typically have bright red plumage on the head, breast, and back
- females and juveniles are generally olive-yellow to gray
- black wings with two white wing bars
- notched tail
- often perch in trees or shrubs

- medium-sized songbird
- black and white plumage (adult males)
- bright rose-red patch on the chest (adult males)
- white underparts with streaks of black
- black wings with white patches (adult males)
- stout, conical bill
- females and immature birds have brown and heavily streaked plumage
- white eyebrow stripe (females and immature birds)

- medium-sized seabird
- black or dark brown plumage
- bright red feet
- white wing patches
- thin, dark bill
- white underwings (visible in flight)
- red inner mouth (during breeding season)
- often seen perched on coastal rocks or swimming in the water

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a California Gull in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- white head and underparts
- grey wings and back
- black wing tips with white spots
- yellowish legs
- yellow bill with a red spot near the tip
- dark eyes with a red eye ring during the breeding season
- slightly forked tail
- feathered body suitable for aquatic environments
- often seen near water bodies

- medium to large size seabird
- predominantly white to light grey plumage
- wings with pale grey tips, lacking black markings
- yellow bill with a red spot on the lower mandible (adults)
- pink legs and feet
- rounded head with a gentle slope
- dark eyes with a thin, red orbital ring
- often seen near coastal areas, usually in flight or standing on the ground
- wingspan wide and broad feathers

useful visual features for distinguishing a Heermann Gull in a photo:
- medium-sized seabird
- dark grey body (non-breeding season)
- light grey body (breeding season)
- white head (breeding season)
- black-tipped, bright red bill
- black legs and feet
- red eye ring
- dark wingtips
- slightly hooked bill

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Herring Gull in a photo:
- medium to large size seabird
- white head, neck, and underparts
- pale grey back and upper wings
- black wingtips with white "mirrors"
- yellow beak with a red spot on the lower mandible
- pale yellow or pinkish legs
- robust body with broad wings
- sharp, slightly curved beak
- piercing, often yellow eyes with a red orbital ring

- pure white plumage
- medium-sized gull
- short, thick bill with a blue/grey base and yellow tip
- dark eyes
- short, rounded wings
- slightly forked tail
- black legs and feet
- often seen in Arctic regions or near sea ice

There are several useful visual features to tell if there is a Ring-billed Gull in a photo:
- Medium-sized bird
- Predominantly white body with grey wings
- Black ring around the yellow bill
- Yellow legs and feet
- Distinctive black wingtips with white spots when wings are spread
- Red orbital ring around the eye
- Rounded head with a short neck
- Often found near water bodies like lakes, rivers, and coastal areas

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Slaty-backed Gull in a photo:
- medium to large size
- dark slate-gray back and wings
- white head and underparts
- yellow bill with a red spot near the tip
- pink legs
- white wingtips with black markings
- yellow eyes with a red ring around them when in breeding plumage
- robust body structure
- typically found in coastal or near-water habitats

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Western Gull in a photo:
- large seabird
- white head, neck, and underparts
- grey wings and back
- black wingtips with small white spots
- yellow bill with a red spot near the tip
- pink legs and feet
- yellowish eyes with a red orbital ring
- relatively stocky body
- typically seen near coastal regions or bodies of water

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Anna Hummingbird in a photo:
- small-sized bird
- iridescent green or bronze-green feathers on the body
- males have a striking rose-pink or reddish crown and throat (gorget)
- females have a more subdued iridescent green and a grayish-white throat area
- both sexes have a relatively short, straight, and thin bill
- rapid wing movement, often blurred in photographs
- can often be seen hovering in mid-air
- a relatively long tail compared to body length
- sleek and slender body shape

- small bird
- iridescent green back and crown
- white or grayish underparts
- adult males have a distinctive ruby-red throat patch
- long, slender beak
- rapid wing movement, often a blur
- tail is relatively short and slightly forked
- often seen hovering near flowers or feeders
- black mask-like stripe through the eyes (more prominent in males)
- relatively short wings compared to other hummingbirds

- Small size (about 3-4 inches in length)
- Bright orange or rust-colored plumage, particularly in males
- Greenish back (mainly in females and immature males)
- Iridescent red throat (gorget) in males
- Long, slender bill adapted for feeding on nectar
- Rapid wing movement, often appearing as a blur in photos
- Often seen hovering near flowers or feeders

- vibrant green plumage
- iridescent blue or violet patch on the sides of the head
- slender, slightly curved bill
- small size, typical of hummingbirds
- rapid wing movement
- forked tail
- often seen hovering near flowers or feeders

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Long-tailed Jaeger in a photo:
- medium-sized seabird
- slender body
- long, pointed wings
- distinctively long, central tail feathers (especially in adults during breeding season)
- dark, cap-like head
- white underparts
- greyish or brownish upperparts
- pale yellow or cream-colored cheeks (adult breeding plumage)

- strongly hooked bill with a pale tip
- dark, sooty brown overall color with lighter underparts
- prominent white "flashes" on the wings during flight
- two central tail feathers extend beyond the rest, forming spoon-shaped tips in adults
- strong, direct flight pattern
- heavy, barrel-chested appearance
- yellowish or light streaks on the nape

- bright blue upperparts and white underparts

- medium-sized body, typically 9-12 inches in length

- medium-sized bird
- blue upperparts including head, wings, and tail

- whitish or light gray throat
- black barring on the back or wings

- bright green upper body

- medium-sized bird

- white belly and flanks
- pink or pale-colored bill

- distinct white outer tail feathers that are visible in flight

- medium-sized bird

- olive-green back and wings

- black, stout bill

- medium-sized bird
- predominantly gray plumage on the back

- black mask extending from the beak through the eyes
- slightly forked tail
- long, straight black beak

- medium-sized bird
- slate blue head and back
- large head with a shaggy crest
- thick, straight bill
- white collar around the neck
- blue and white plumage, with a blue breast band (males) or an additional rust-colored band on the belly (females)

- white underparts
- chest band: males have a broad white chest band while females often have additional rufous (reddish-brown) markings

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Pied Kingfisher in a photo:
- medium-sized bird
- black and white plumage
- distinctive black and white crest on the head
- long, straight bill
- black mask extending from the bill through the eyes

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Red-legged Kittiwake in a photo:
- seabird
- medium-sized
- pale grey back and wings
- white head and body
- black wingtips
- short, deep red legs

- slightly forked tail
- yellow bill

- small to medium-sized bird

- yellow or yellowish-white face and throat
- black mask and bib
- white underparts
- streaked back and wings

There are several useful visual features to tell there is a Pacific Loon in a photo:
- medium-sized waterbird
- streamlined body
- black-and-white checkered back during breeding season
